	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    General Tactics: Fighting Methods</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:ravenseyrie@hotmail.com">Shannon J. Lane</a> | 
		            11/19/2001 2:16:29 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Greetings and salutations fellow Norathians!<BR>
<BR>
I do not pretend to be a true expert in all things Everquest, but, in reading through all of the guides here (or at least those that caught my eye), I noticed a distinct lack of anything resembling tactics and how they work in various situations.  What follows here will be a rather abbreviated list of all of the things I've learned in my slow crawl through 34 levels - everything that's worked, in what situation, how to do it, and how to teach others what you're attempting.<BR>
<BR>
I don't pretend that this will be an exhaustively complete guide, but I think this will serve as a refresher course for the older veterans - and a bit of a leg up for the new folks, so that you can see and understand how it all works.  At the very least - I hope you enjoy, and I hope this serves to help all of my fellow adventurers in their quest to see everything norrath has to offer.. and perhaps keep you from dying quite so often as well.<BR>
<BR>
Note that I make no references to classes, levels, or equipment here - I've learned that just about anyone can use just about all of these tactics.. provided they look for the right items or luck into being able to use the spells.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Let's start with the Basics:<BR>
<BR>
1)  Beatdown.<BR>
<BR>
Hey, this one's simple - and the only thing most of us have before level five.  Target a mob.  Melee and/or nuke said mob, continue until mob drops or you do.<BR>
<BR>
It's the most basic tactic, and the one from which all others are born.  It's the /most/ equipment-dependant, and the one you lose the soonest - after  you grow up a bit, this sort of play is just going to get you killed.  But.. it's a beginning.<BR>
<BR>
2) Root bombing<BR>
<BR>
Another fairly easy combat tactic, root bombing is nearly as simple:  using spell or item, root the mob in place.  Then, pound from a distance with spell, bow, or thrown weapon until the enemy dies or your root breaks - refreshing root if you must.<BR>
<BR>
One small detail deserves special mention:  Rooted Mobs Never Stop Fighting.  Even if the mob has been damaged enough to turn and run, if it cannot, and you get in range, it /will/ try to kill you.  Often, when the mob is attempting to flee (noticible by the fact that even in the root it turns its back on you) it is better to allow the root to break than renew it - it will save much damage over the long term if you're in a situation requiring you to get close.<BR>
<BR>
This scores over Beatdown in one major respect - the mob can't hit you if it's not in melee range.<BR>
<BR>
The disadvantage?  Root a caster, and watch it tear  you to shreds.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
3) Kiting<BR>
<BR>
Ah - the first /real/ fighting technique, and one that has been much bandied about for some time.  Kiting's actually fairly simple though.  <BR>
<BR>
Kiting requires that you have /some/ form of ranged attack, and some sort of speed buff (SoW is by far the best) and/or some way of slowing down the mob (Snares, or their equivalent).  Hit the mob at maximum range with whatever is appropriate at the moment, then retreat from the mob, staying out of its melee range, pounding with arrows, spells, rocks, the kitchen sink - whatever it takes.<BR>
<BR>
A far more reliable method than Root Bombing, Kiting gives you far more control over the situation.  You can take the mob where you'd like -turn and run if you must, move your fighting area if you must.. and more.  With a short-duration root - you can even sit and rest or meditate in the middle of the fight and still have time to jump up and get your bearings before having to scoot off again.<BR>
<BR>
DoT's work exceptionally well in this situation, as well, giving you complete control over the mob and its health constantly dropping without you having to do much beyond stay out of the way and refresh the DoT on occasion.<BR>
<BR>
A few provisos - Kiting can be dangerous, and is best done in wide-open areas with good visibility.  Many's the time /I've/ been killed in cresting a hill with a cyclops behind me only to run face-first into a hill-giant's knee.  Gah!  Know the area, know where you're going, and never.. never... never panic.  You must learn when a kite goes bad, and know when it's better to get out of dodge than to face several angry bad guys with your death on their mind.<BR>
<BR>
Do /not/ kite in dungeons.  Ever. *shudder*<BR>
<BR>
4) Fear Kiting<BR>
<BR>
Fear kiting is an advanced form of standard kiting - simply set up as though you were kiting the mob, get your speed up or its speed down.. and then /fear/ the mob into running away from you.  Several spells do this, as do several items and the Instill Doubt ability.<BR>
<BR>
Arguably the safest and most effective form of kiting, fear kiting gives even /more/ control over the situation.  Don't like which way the mob's running?  Retreat and wait for the fear to end, then refear it another direction.  <BR>
<BR>
You're in melee, too - which means even /more/ damage over time than standard kiting - /and/ you don't have to constantly worry about which keys to press - more of your attention is on your surroundings.<BR>
<BR>
Deadly and efficient, fear kiting is also a great deal of fun.<BR>
<BR>
Group Tactics:<BR>
<BR>
in a group, you have to start looking at other creative ways of doing things.  Standard group policy dictates a certain way of playing  - this will challenge that a bit, and offer a few alternatives.  Be aware, though - that these are just ideas, and require a /good/ hunting group - when playing witha pick-up group, it may be best to simply follow the standard party line, rather than suddenly get creative.  Use your judgement.<BR>
<BR>
1)  pack Fear Kiting.<BR>
<BR>
Hey - take a good fear kite, throw in three more melee'ers, watch the mobs /drop/. *grin* Same tactics as above, but /this/ time more damage is getting done - what's not to like?<BR>
<BR>
2)  Circle Taunting<BR>
<BR>
Current mentality says that the group's warrior should be a damage sponge.  However, why should he have to take it all?   Clerics, Hybrids, and even /casters/ can absorb punshiment in varying degrees - and circle taunting is an efficient way to spread out a Mob's damage. (we'll get to /why/ you'd want to do this at the end of the section)<BR>
<BR>
Circle taunting takes a bit more finesse than most techniques, and is best used in a dungeon or other area in which kiting and fear kiting are ineffecient, or against mobs that hit hard but fall down easily.  Implementing is rather simple.. but a bit tricky to get timed, and elegant when it happens.<BR>
<BR>
Simply:<BR>
<BR>
The primary tank engages the mob - preferablly pulling it.  This makes the mob /quite/ angry at him - and the mob gives this poor fellow its full attention.  At this point, the secondary tanks and damage dealers do their thing.<BR>
<BR>
During the course of the fight, the secondary tanks taunt and/or use taunt abilities until the mob /turns to face them/.  The primary tank continues to taunt as well - it should turn back immediately when the primary tank taunts one more time.  The moment you see this.. circle taunting has begun.<BR>
<BR>
Start timing the mob's swings - hit or miss, have the primary and secondary tanks taunt in rotation as the mob fights.. and watch as the mob hits each of you in turn!  One hit to the fighter, one to the ranger, one to the pally, and back around the circle.  In the meantime, the poor thing has /three/ people dealing damage to it at an extreme rate, with casters throwing spells in over the top.<BR>
<BR>
Add a regeneration effect to the fighters, and the casters suddenly don't have to /heal/ them anymore.. as no one's taking enough damage /fast/ enough to make it something to worry about.  Even without a healer, your downtime is reduced - if your puller's only down one red instead of three, he can likely go right back out and pull /again/.<BR>
<BR>
Circle taunting too /fast/ or /slow/ means the damage isn't well distributed, and it's something of a wasted effort.  <BR>
<BR>
Now - other than the above - here's one more good reason to try this one:  Mobs have more hitpoints than any one member of your party.<BR>
<BR>
A sabretooth grimalkyn from the Lake of ill Omen has something in excess of 1500hps!  Your three warriors together probably have about the same, if not more.. and it's going to deal as much damage, if not more, than your group in each combat round.<BR>
<BR>
Spread the wealth, live longer. Have your group fight as one creature with a lot of abilites, and the enemies can't really hurt you.<BR>
<BR>
3) Loop Kiting<BR>
<BR>
A variant of standard kiting - Loop Kiting is kiting with a group.<BR>
<BR>
Standard kiting tactics are ineffective when coupled with a fast pulling hunting ground and six people trying to chase and/or run from a mob in the midst of hostile territory.<BR>
<BR>
Loop kiting, however, addresses the issue.  Again, a tricky tactic, loop kiting involves a puller that can begin a standard kite against a single mob.  That puller then begins to circle the party at the extreme range of spell and bow, doing everything they can to keep the mob mad at /them.. which generally means staying /just/ outside of the mob's melee range so that the puller is constantly closer to it than the party is.<BR>
<BR>
The puller should kite as though the party weren't there, as well - if the puller doesn't consistantly do damage, the mob will eventually get fed up and go after the pack that is the group.. with often messy results.<BR>
<BR>
Loop kiting enables a group with enough time to safely take down mobs that are unsafe to melee - think griffons or Giants - due to their high damage output versus their relative level.  It can be used on red mobs as well and at any time the casting types will need more than one run of mana to deal with the problem.<BR>
<BR>
The disadvantage?  Loop kiting is a slow way to kill something, and /very/ precision work - if the aggro breaks, your group's in /trouble/.  <BR>
<BR>
4) Hate Kiting<BR>
<BR>
Again, a difficult game, Hate Kiting is arguably one of the single most /fun/ ways to kite a mob in the game.<BR>
<BR>
In this particular technique, perfect for use with partners, both partners make the mob /mad/.. and set it up as though getting ready to kite.  You need the circle-taunt level of aggro, and you need the mob slowed... then, the two partners bracket the mob, one to either side, both inside the mob's assist radius.<BR>
<BR>
Have the one that /isn't/ currently being chased by the mob sit down.<BR>
<BR>
The mob will immediately turn and chase the 'medder', leaving the other fellow to charge into its back!  The medder waits until either the mob is on top of him, or the beastie decides to hate his friend more.. then hops up and either retreats.. or he himself jumps into the mob, as it's suddenly being pulled the other way.<BR>
<BR>
Repeat until the mob is so confused it doesn't know who to chase, and gives up and runs.<BR>
<BR>
This one takes /precise/ coordination and a /very/ good hunting partner - don't attempt this one early, and expect to have to practice it a bit until you learn all of its limitations...<BR>
<BR>
.. the look on a giant's face as he goes red from anger is worth it, though.<BR>
<BR>
Hey - this is a beginning.  Next time, I'll pop on and talk about party saving techniques, and ways to manage that overpull without a chanter.<BR>
<BR>
We'll talk about 'parking', 'ghetto parking', 'root spiking', and insanity defense.. 'till then, I hope this helps, and lends a bit more fun to the wilds of Norrath!<BR>
<BR>
Montaigne Wolfstorm<BR>
Level 34 Ranger, Morrell-Thule<BR>
<BR>

